Exercise 2 (9pts)

The financial world operates with many different currencies, and for countries to trade, for people to travel, these currencies are converted, bought and sold. The web site https://openexchangerates.org/ provides access to (daily) cross rates of currencies relative to the USD. The data is provided in JSON form. With a free account you can pull 30 days worth of data, every day. Carson Sievert’s web site explains how to do this, and provides R code. To follow the instructions and get your own data you need to sign up for an instant free account, and use the key provided to get the data.

  1. (2pts) Between your group members pull at least 80 days of cross-rates. Turn this in with your lab report.

  2. (2pts) Use the lubridate package data handling routines to make R recognise the date column as a date. If you write out the data and read it in using read_csv then the date will be recognised as a date.

  3. Make a time series plot of the currency of your choice, for the period of data that you have downloaded. Describe the fluctuation in the rates over the time. Something like this: The Indian rupee has declined a small amount of this time, which corresponds to strengthening relative to the USD.

  1. (3pts) Compare and contrast the Australian dollar fluctuations with this currency. Make a plot or two to help with your description. The Indian rupee and the Australian dollar have a very similar pattern, except for the very last point where the rupee gained substantially more relative to the USD.

  1. (3pts) Make the map of electorates coloured by size.
library(ggthemes)
nat_data <- sF@data
nat_data$id <- row.names(nat_data)
nat_map$group <- paste("g",nat_map$group,sep=".")
nat_map$piece <- paste("p",nat_map$piece,sep=".")
nms <- sFsmall@data %>% select(Elect_div, State)
nms$id <- as.character(1:150)

ggplot(aes(map_id=id), data=nat_data) +
  geom_map(aes(fill=Area_SqKm), map=nat_map) +
  expand_limits(x=nat_map$long, y=nat_map$lat) + 
  theme_map()

  1. Extract the information about the electorates from the shape files. Extract the centroids for each electorate, and combine these two.
polys <- as(sF, "SpatialPolygons")
centroid <- function(i, polys) {
  ctr <- Polygon(polys[i])@labpt
  data.frame(long_c=ctr[1], lat_c=ctr[2])
}
centroids <- seq_along(polys) %>% purrr::map_df(centroid, polys=polys)
nat_data <- bind_cols(nat_data, centroids)
  1. (3pts) Plot the centroids overlaid on the map of electorates.
